  "output": "I have enough to write the analysis — 132 configured sources, many paginating up to 40 pages of ~10-20 jobs each, feeding into a per-row SQLite loop. Here's the breakdown.\n\n## jobsquare performance analysis\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper (no React/frontend exists in this repo, so I've mapped the requested categories onto their closest equivalents: N+1 SQL, redundant per-item computation, caching, and resource/leak patterns).\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nOne `SELECT` per job, executed serially. With 132 configured sources and several fetchers paginating up to 40 pages (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix, Eightfold, ByteDance), a single run can push thousands of jobs through this loop — thousands of individual round-trips instead of one query.\n\n**Fix:** batch-load existing rows into a dict once, then diff in-memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):          # stay under SQLite's 999-var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(\n            (r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"])\n            for r in cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk)\n        )\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(n) queries into O(n/900) + O(n) in-memory dict lookups.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-12, 44-54`\n\n```python\ndef _compile(words): return [re.compile(...) for w in words if w]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)): return False\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)): return False\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` recompiles the same `include`/`exclude` regex lists from scratch on *every single job*. For a large fetch this is thousands of redundant `re.compile()` calls for identical patterns.\n\n**Fix:** compile once outside the loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = None, exclude: list[re.Pattern] = None, ...):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude): return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include): return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Caching opportunity — pagination doesn't stop at \"already known\" (`fetchers.py`, most `fetch_*` functions)\n\nFetchers like `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_eightfold` sort results newest-first (`sort=recent` / `sort_by=timestamp`) and paginate up to `max_pages` (e.g. Amazon defaults to 40 pages × 10 = 400 requests worth of listings) — but the `seen` set only dedupes *within the current run*, not against what's already in `jobs.db`. Every scheduled run (per README, this runs every 12h) re-fetches and re-parses the full page depth even though most postings haven't changed.\n\n**Fix:** since these feeds are sorted newest-first, thread the store's known keys into the fetcher and stop paginating once a full page returns only already-seen `external_id`s:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_amazon(client, source, known_ids: set[str] = frozenset()) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    for pg in range(max_pages):\n        data = await _get_json(...)\n        jobs_raw = (data or {}).get(\"jobs\") or []\n        batch = parse_amazon(company, jobs_raw)\n        fresh = [j for j in batch if j.external_id not in seen]\n        if not fresh:\n            break\n        seen.update(j.external_id for j in fresh)\n        jobs.extend(fresh)\n        if known_ids and all(j.external_id in known_ids for j in batch):\n            break   # hit the tail of already-known postings — stop early\n    return jobs\n```\n\nThis is the single biggest win available: it cuts steady-state network calls (and the risk of getting rate-limited/blocked by these ATS platforms) from \"re-walk the whole board\" to \"walk until you hit familiar territory.\"\n\n### 4. Blocking I/O inside the async pipeline — `notify.py` + `pipeline.py:44`\n\n```python\n# pipeline.py\nwith Store(cfg[\"db\"]) as store:\n    new, changed = store.diff(jobs)\n    dispatch(new, changed)      # <-- sync call inside `async def run`\n```\n\n`dispatch` (`notify.py:105-110`) calls `notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, `notify_email`, `notify_sms` — all of which use blocking `httpx.post(...)` / `smtplib.SMTP(...)`. Each of these:\n- Blocks the asyncio event loop for the duration of the call (defeats the point of `fetch_all` being async).\n- Opens a brand-new connection per call via the `httpx.post()` module-level convenience function — no connection reuse, even though webhook/Slack notifications could share a client across a run.\n\n**Fix:** either run notifiers in a thread (`asyncio.to_thread`) or convert them to `httpx.AsyncClient` and `await` them from `run()`:\n\n```python\nasync def dispatch(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(timeout=15) as client:\n        for fn in (notify_console, notify_slack, notify_webhook, notify_sms):\n            try:\n                await asyncio.to_thread(fn, new, changed)  # or native async versions\n            except Exception as e:\n                print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n```\n\nLow-severity today since notifier lists are small, but it's on the hot path of every scheduled run and will get worse if notifier volume grows.\n\n### 5. Minor redundant computation — `models.py:55-69` (`Job.key` / `Job.content_hash`)\n\nBoth are `@property`, recomputed on every access rather than cached. `store.diff()` accesses `job.key` for the lookup, then `to_row()` (called from `_insert`/`_update`) recomputes both `key` and `content_hash` (a SHA-256 hash) again. Cheap per-call, but adds up at thousands-of-jobs scale and is free to fix:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _key: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def key(self) -> str:\n        if self._key is None:\n            self._key = f\"{self.source}:{self.company}:{self.external_id}\"\n        return self._key\n```\n(Only worth doing if profiling actually shows this matters — at sub-microsecond cost per call it's the lowest-priority item here.)\n\n### Memory leaks — none found\n`Store` connections are consistently closed via context managers (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:_store`), `fetch_all` closes its owned `httpx.AsyncClient` in a `finally` block (`fetchers.py:1142-1146`), and there are no unbounded caches or growing global state. This is a short-lived batch script, so classic \"leak\" patterns (unclosed sockets accumulating over a long-running process) don't really apply here — the main cost centers are query count, redundant recompilation, and re-fetching data you already have, as above.\n\n### Priority order\n1. **#1 (N+1 diff query)** — biggest, easiest win, zero behavior change.\n2. **#3 (early-exit pagination)** — biggest real-world impact (network cost + rate-limit risk), but needs the store's known-keys threaded into `fetch_all`/`fetch_source`.\n3. **#2 (regex recompilation)** — trivial fix, real if `include_keywords`/`exclude_keywords` are used.\n4. **#4 (blocking notifiers)** — only matters as notifier count/volume grows.\n5. **#5** — skip unless profiling says otherwise.\n",
